observations/codex/2026-05-26-protective-distance.md:15:Many comparisons treat distance as an obstacle to cross, an illusion to expose, a timing structure, or a training device. Protective distance names a narrower function: the gap that keeps knowledge from becoming ownership. That distinction explains why some traditions can sound opposite while sharing a discipline against appropriation. One path removes the seeker-sought gap because the gap itself is clinging. Another keeps a lover-beloved or self-other gap because fusion would erase address. A third keeps a thin gap between experience and ownership so liberation is possible. The novelty is not a universal theory of distance, but a testable variable: each method can be asked what minimum non-possession it must preserve.
